Title: The Genus Tydeus: Subgenera and Species Groups withDescriptions of New Species (Acarina: Tydeidae).
Journal: Annals of the Entomological Society of America
Notiz:
The genus Tydeus Koch is revised. The subgeneric
structure is discussed, and 3 subgenera are used: AFRO-
TYDEUS, n.subg.; PERTYDEUS André & Naud.; and TYDEUS
s.str. The following new species are described: T.
kenyensis, T.meyerae, T.nicaraguensis, T. argentinensis
T.mumai, T.australensis, T.georgiensis, T.costaricensis
T.oregonensis, T.mississippiensis, T.africanus,
T.taiwanensis, T.lambi, T.costensis, T.ricensis, T.
turrialbensis, and T.chilensis. Some other previously
known species are discussed.

Title: Sex Ratio and Sex Determination in the American HouseDust Mite, Dermatophagoides farinae.
Journal: Annals of the Entomological Society of America
Notiz:
The relative proportion of males was 0,474 from
brother-sister matings and 0,454 from outcross matings
for the American house dust mite, Dermatophagoides
farinae Hughes. Relative proportions of 0,308 and
0,539 are reported for cultures 0,5 and 5 yr of age,
respectively. Sex determination by sex chromosomes
is consistent with the observed sex ratios and the
properties of the familial frequency distribution.

Handwritten:

Cunaxidae is revised. Nine genera are recognized as
comprising the family, and 4 of these, Neocunaxoides,
Pseudobonzia, Parabonzia, and Pseudocunaxa, are newly
erected. Descriptions and illustrations are presented
for each genus. Translations of generic descriptions
are included for Coleoscirus Berlese and Cunaxoides
(Koch). A redescription is given for Dactyloscirus:

Notiz:
Abstract: A new arboreal oribatid mite, Phauloppia
adjecta, was found in colonies on bark of bead-trees
in the area of Tsu, Central Japan. The new species is
distinguishable from the known congeners by the
presence of 5 pairs of areae porosae and long
flagelliform notogastral setae h1 and h2

including G.xarifae Strenzke, are also summarized in

Title: Fine Structure of External "Genital" Papillae in theFreshwater Mite Hydrovolzia placophora (Hydrovolziidae,Actinedida,Actinotrichida,Acari).
Notiz:
Numerous "genital" papillae are described for the first
time in the freshwater mite Hydrovolzia placophora. In
contrast to other actinotrichid mites, these organs
are located on the epimeral plates, thus well removed
from the genital opening. Ultrastructurally, the
papillae correspond to those of ther freshwater mites
and are thus likely involved in ion/osmoregulation.

Title: RESPIRATORY ORGANS OF ORIBATID MITES
Handwritten:
RESPIRATORY ORGANS OF ORIBATID MITES.
Atypus, Nr. 58: 5-12.
Subclass Acari is subdivided into seven orders based
on situation and condition of tracheal organs.
One of the orders Cryptostigmata (or Oribatida)
seems a heterogenous group about the organs and the
other feature-s. The present paper gives an outline
of the respiratory organs of oribatid mites based
on many works of GRANDJEAN and several ones of some
other authors.

species, stage of mite, occurrence in month and
localisation.

kurosawai, is described from Yonezawa of Yamagata

of lamellar cusps and the location of interlamellar

Terrestrial arthropods from Vestfjella, Dronning MaudLand (Acari, Collembola), with notes on their taxonomy.
Handwritten:
Six species of prostigmate mites were collected from
Vestfjella, Dronning Maud Land in Antarctica. These
were Eupodes tottanfjella Strandtmann, Protereunetes
maudae Strandtmann, Tydeus setsukoae Strandtmann,
T.erebus Strandtmann. Nanorchestes bifurcatus Strandt-
mann and N.brekkerista Strandtmann & Sømme. Notes on
their taxonomy and distribution are presented. In
addition, the collection also contained one species
of Collembola: Cryptopygus antarcticus Willem.

Title: Über einige Wassermilben von St. Vincent, West-Indien
Handwritten:
A collection of water mites from St. Vincent, West
Indies, was found to comprise 4 species, viz.Limnesia
minuscula Ribaga, Neotyrrelia petricola Lundblad,
Hygrobates ampliatus Viets, and Corticacarus
(Polycorticacarellus) harrisoni n.sp. The three known
speices are neotropical and the new species has South
American affinities.

caridae of New York. 23 species and 2 subspecies are
described and illustrated from the collections made
at Long Island and eastern New York. Of these, 14
species of Scutacarus Gros, and 7 species and 1 sub-
species of Imparipes Berlese are new to science, and
3 European
species are new records. Imparipes apicola
(Banks) is

mainly the
free-living predaceous, or fungivorous
species. 102 figures are presented.

A NEW SPECIES OF TARSONEMUS
FROM STORED GRAIN
(ACARINA: TARSONEMIDAE).
The Canadian Entomologist, Bd. 104: 1699-1708.
Original-Abstract
The female and male of Tarsonemus granarius n.sp.
are described and ilustrated. This mite occurs in
granaries in Canada, Japan, and the British Isles.
It feeds on, and perhaps disseminates, fungi that
deteriorate grain stored for prolonged periods.
Similarities and differences in the morphology and
ecology of adults of this species and of T.fusarii
Cooreman are discussed.

Title: Effect of reafforestation by conifers in naturalbiotopes of middle and South Navarra (NorthernSpain).
Notiz:
The effects on soil fauna (Nematoda, Oribatei and
Collembola) of reafforestation with Pinus nigra and
Pinus halepensis, in two sites of Middle and South
Navarra have been studied. The analysis of Equitabi-
lity, Richness and Similarity, as well as comparisons
among biotopes by means of correspondences analysis,
have been made.

Title: Neue und interessante Milben aus dem Genfer MuseumXLI. Vierter Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Oribatiden-Fauna Griechenlands (Acari: Oribatida).
Notiz:
The Oribatids form 14 soil samples (collected in
1977 and 1978 as part of the soil investigation pro-
gram of the Geneve Museum in continental Greece and
the greek islands) have been studied and 52 species
and subspecies identified of which 16 have proved to
be new to science: Mesoplophora (1sp.); Archiphthira-
carus (1sp.); Hoplophthiracarus (2sp.); Steganacarus
(4sp.); Euphthiracarus (1sp.); Brachychochthonius
(2sp.); Eobrachychthonius (1sp.); Plesiodamaeus
(1sp.); Nellacarus (1sp.); Damaeolus (1sp.); Xenillus
(1sp.).First zoogeographical conclusions are given.

Title: Neue und interessante Milben aus dem Genfer MuseumXXXVIII. Oribatids (Acari) from Monte Susana (Tierradel Fuego, Argentina).
Notiz:
From four soil samples taken on the Mount Susana
near Ushuaia 29 Oribatid species have been identified,
17 of them are described as new to science. It was
necessary to establish 4 new genera (Antarctoplophora,
Fuegoplophora, Neoprotophthiracarus in the family
Phthiracaridae and Hauseroceratoppia in the family
Metrioppiidae). Ecological and zoogeographical
analyses are given.

n.sp., is described from specimens collected from
Senecio litter on volcan Karisimbi, Zaire. This is the
first record of Holonothrus outside the Australasian
region. Neotropical records of Holonothrus (Chile,
Venezuela,Dominica) and Crotonia (Brazil, Colombia,
Panama, Costa Rica and Mexico) are also included.

Title: The Halacarid fauna (Halacaridae,Acari) of Bermuda'sCaves.
Notiz:
Nine species of halacarid mites (Halacaridae,Acari)
are here reported from inland marine caves on Bermuda.
Five of these are new species, e.g. Agauopsis bermu-
densis, A.littoralis, Copidognathus bermudensis,
C.subterraneus, and C.longispinus, while two species,
Copidognathus floridensis and Simognathus fuscus, are
new recorded for Bermuda.Probably none of these
halacarids are true caverniclous forms.

Title: Die Wirkung der Klärschlammrotte auf die Bodenmilben.
Journal: Zeitschrift für Morphologie und Ökologie der Tiere
Notiz:
Frischer Klärschlamm (pH 5) ist von Milben nicht bewohnt. Nach 4monatiger Lagerung
(pH 6-7) tritt eine Anoetus-Art als Erstbesiedler 
auf. Einige Wochen später folgen Uropodinen,
Laelantiden und Parasitiden; Oribatiden 
meiden den Schlamm. Abgelagerter Klärschlamm, der
als Dünger in Versuchsparzellen eingebracht 
wird, bewirkt anfangs ein merkbares Absinken der
Milbenpopulation; erst nach 4-5 
Monaten ist der Zahlenwert des ungedüngten Bodens wieder
erreicht. Beide Böden unterscheiden sich 
jedoch voneinander durch die anders geartete gruppen-
mäßige Zusammensetzung ihrer 
Milbenfauna. Im gedüngten Boden erfahren Oribotiden,
Nanorchestiden und Prostigmata eine 
deutliche zahlenmäßige Schwächung zugunsten der Gama-
sinen, Laelaptiden, Tarsonemini, Acaridien 
und Uropodinen, die vom Verf. als „Klärschlamm-
freunde bezeichnet werden. Der 
so gedüngte Boden erweist sich bei Spinat-Aussaat als keim-
lingshemmend; bei Rettichpflanzen kommt es zu 
einer Steigerung des Laubgewichtes ohne Ge-
☐ 
wichtszunahme der Rüben. Die 
Düngung mit kompostiertem Klärschlamm führt zu einer
Populationssteigerung, ohne daß es zu 
einem auffallend starken Überwiegen der „Klärschlamm-
freunde kommt. Die geernteten Rettiche 
haben im Vergleich zur normalen Klärschlamm-
düngung ein günstigeres Laub: Rüben-Gewichtsverhältnis
. Noch besser Ergebnisse liefert die
Düngung mit schnell getrocknetem 
Klärschlamm; der Ertrag ist sogar günstiger als bei Stall-
mist oder Kompostzugabe. Verschiedener 
Mineralzusatz führt in den untersuchten Böden zu
R. Schuster (Graz).
merkbaren Änderungen in der Milbenpopulation
.

Title: Notes on the morphology of Alycus roseus C.L. Koch.
Notiz:
Es wird hier eine genaue und komplette Beschreibung
von Alycus roseus C.L. Koch ((= Pachygnathus dugesi
Grandjean) (Acari) gegeben. Die Art gehört zu den En-
deostigmata, eine primitive Gruppe der Actinedida (=
Trombidiformes). Die Beschreibung ist so aufgebaut,
daß sie einen Vergleich zwischen primitiven Vertretern
der Actinotrichida und der Anacthnotrichida ermöglicht.
Sie ist zugleich ein Grundstudium der Segmentierung
und der Somaterminologie bei den Actinotrichida. Es
wird mit besonderer Sorgfalt die Homologie der dorsa-
len Setae, der Genital- und der Sejugalzonen beachtet,
wobei die letztgenannte mit einem Endosternit in Ver-
bindung steht. Neue Benennungen werden vorgeschlagen
wie Stethosoma für das Prosoma ohne Gnathosoma, Pro-,

Title: Aggression and Mating Success in Male Spider Mites.
Handwritten:
Male Tetranychus urticae search for and defend
quiescent pharate females. Intruding males may be
threatened or attacked.Fights involve pushing and
grappling with the forelegs, jousting with the mouth-
parts, and entangling the opponent with silk. In these
encounters larger males usually win. Sole possession
of a female at her ecdysis virtually ensures success-
ful mating.
